 performance and offers studies showing that performance pay cannot improve performance on the kind of tasks companies ask of their CEOs. Moreover, CEOs of large established companies do not typically have much impact on their companies’ results. In this eye-opening exposé, Dorff argues that companies should give up on the decades-long experiment to mold compensation into a corporate governance tool and maps out a rationale for returning to the era of guaranteed salaries.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aChief executive officersxSalaries, etc. 0aCompensation managementzUnited States. 0aExecutivesxSalaries, etc.zUnited States. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Economy.2bisacsh  aamerican business.  aamerican economy.  abehavioral theory.  abig business.  aboard members.  abosses.  abusiness.  acapitalism.  aceos.  achief executive officer.  acompensation.  acorporate culture.  acorporate directors.  acorporate governance tools.  acorporate performance.  acorporations.  aeconomists.  aeconomy.  aera of guaranteed salaries.  aexecutive pay.  ahuman resource professionals.  alarge salaries.  aleadership.  amotivation.  aperformance pay.  aproject management.  astock options.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015z97831106211120 cprintz978052028101140uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052095859340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520958593423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520958593/original  a978-3-11-062111-2  University of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY